gold_text:
Since there are twelve steps between $(0,0)$ and $(5,7)$, $A$ and $B$ can meet only after they have each moved six steps. The possible meeting places are $P_{0} = (0,6)$, $P_{1} = (1,5)$, $P_{2} = (2,4)$, $P_{3}=(3,3)$, $P_{4} = (4,2)$, and $P_{5} =
(5,1)$. Let $a_{i}$ and $b_{i}$ denote the number of paths to $P_{i}$ from $(0,0)$ and $(5,7)$, respectively. Since $A$ has to take $i$ steps to the right and $B$ has to take $i+1$ steps down, the number of ways in which $A$ and $B$ can meet at $P_{i}$ is $$a_{i}\cdot b_{i} = \binom{6}{i} \binom{6}{i+1}. $$Since $A$ and $B$ can each take $2^{6}$ paths in six steps, the probability that they meet  is \begin{align*}
&\sum_{i = 0}^{5}\displaystyle\left ( \frac{a_{i}}{2^{6}}\displaystyle\right)\displaystyle\left( \frac{b_{i}}{2^{6}} \displaystyle\right) \\
& \qquad = \frac{\binom{6}{0}\binom{6}{1} + \binom{6}{1}\binom{6}{2} + \binom{6}{2}\binom{6}{3}
+ \binom{6}{3}\binom{6}{4}+ \binom{6}{4}\binom{6}{5} + \binom{6}{5}\binom{6}{6}}{2^{12}}\\
& \qquad = \frac{99}{512} \\
& \qquad \approx \boxed{0.20}.
\end{align*}

